summary: there is this post that is going around that is like “the great plot twist of detective pikachu is that there is no plot twist”...
body:
there is this post that is going around that is like “the great plot twist of detective pikachu is that there is no plot twist” but i think it misses the point. like. there ARE plot twists in detective pikachu! mewtwo not being the one to overturn the car, mewtwo being the one to save harry’s life/put it on pikachu, the old white man being evil, his son being a ditto…those WERE plot twists! but they weren’t plot twists to the audience, they were plot twist to the characters.

like. anyone who’s watched any pokemon content knows mewtwo isn’t evil, as much as he hates humanity, so the set up of him being the villain would never work with the audience because we KNOW mewtwo had his redemption arc already, but the people *in universe* don’t know that. we see the ditto in the beginning of the movie and we immediately know it’s gonna chekhov’s gun the shit out of us. they didn’t set out to ~subvert expectations~, because like any pokemon game, the ending wasn’t important, what was important was the journey there

summary: It’s easy to turn your nose up at Ryan Reynolds as Detective Pikachu and Jim Carrey as Doctor Robotnik and Will Smith as Genie...
body: It’s easy to turn your nose up at Ryan Reynolds as Detective Pikachu and Jim Carrey as Doctor Robotnik and Will Smith as Genie but after all the grimdark, pseudo-intellectual media that’s been over-saturating the market for well over a decade, it’s refreshing to just watch some visual junk food and watch celebrated veteran actors take the piss out of themselves for an hour-and-a-half for a change.

summary: You know Detective Pikachu is brilliant when it isn’t content with just avoiding the dreaded “uncanny valley” effect with its...
body:
You know Detective Pikachu is brilliant when it isn’t content with just avoiding the dreaded “uncanny valley” effect with its pokemon designs, it also goes out of its way to use the uncanny valley to its advantage. You probably know wich sequences I’m talking about. One was used heavily in the trailers, while the other one from the climax was kept a secret.

It kind of reminds me of the original Toy Story, actually: the people behind it were aware of the limitations of cgi at the time and avoided the uncanny valley by making the protagonists toys; but they also went out of their way to use the uncanny valley to their advantage by making the antagonists a human kid and a dog, wich looked creepy and wrong and that drove the point home that they were the bad guys (notice how the “good” humans had their faces out of focus most of the time).

Toy Story proved that cgi could be used for feature-lenght animated movies in more ways than one. Detective Pikachu proved that a series like Pokemon can in fact be made in live action, and any creature can be used to their full potential even if not all of them are cute and traditionally appealing like Pikachu. They both knew when to avoid and when to use the uncanny valley effect.
